{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659267"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:04:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:04:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20859"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20859"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.9,0,0.1,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13734"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97377"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13734"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20859"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79992"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"},{"type":"tags","id":"12340"},{"type":"tags","id":"12677"},{"type":"tags","id":"12678"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33056"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33057"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97377"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EProstate-specific antigen (PSA) is commonly used as a tumour marker in clinical practice.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes prostate-specific antigen as a tumour marker?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["It provides definitive diagnosis of prostate cancer","It can be elevated in both malignant and benign conditions","It is exclusively produced by malignant prostate cells","It has high specificity for prostate cancer","It is not detectable in men without prostate disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that PSA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecan be elevated in both malignant and benign conditions\u003C/strong\u003E. PSA is a glycoprotein produced by prostate epithelial cells in both normal and diseased states. While PSA levels often increase in prostate cancer, elevation can also occur in:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBenign prostatic hyperplasia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EProstatitis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFollowing digital rectal examination\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAfter ejaculation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWith increasing age\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt provides definitive diagnosis of prostate cancer\u003C/strong\u003E - PSA elevation alone cannot diagnose cancer and requires confirmation with prostate biopsy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is exclusively produced by malignant prostate cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Both normal and malignant prostate tissue produce PSA\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt has high specificity for prostate cancer\u003C/strong\u003E - PSA lacks specificity due to elevation in multiple benign conditions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is not detectable in men without prostate disease\u003C/strong\u003E - Healthy men have detectable PSA levels that typically increase with age\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe poor specificity of PSA and potential for overdiagnosis has led to ongoing debate about its optimal use in prostate cancer screening.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Prostate-specific antigen (PSA) is a glycoprotein produced by prostate epithelial cells that can be elevated in both benign and malignant conditions.","PSA elevation alone is not diagnostic of prostate cancer and requires further investigation.","Normal prostate tissue produces detectable levels of PSA, which increases with age and prostate size."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; page 335."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79992"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20859"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79992"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T13:21:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T13:24:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13734"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97377"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11597"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Neoplasia","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":6,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12340"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Laboratory diagnosis","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-15T23:41:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-15T23:41:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedi